Odd and even trials listed in order of presentation separately for each
trial-type and test block. This facilitates calculation of split-half
reliability. First, calculate separate mean latencies for odd and then
even trials for each trial-type within each block (i.e., 2 blocks = 16
means; 4 blocks = 32 means; 6 blocks = 48 means.) Difference scores* can
then be calculated for each pair of consistent and inconsistent blocks
for each trial type for both odd and even trials (i.e., 2 blocks = 8
difference scores; 4 blocks = 16 difference scores; 6 blocks = 24
difference scores). Each participant thus provides pairs of difference
scores (one from odd trials and the other from even trials) for the same
trial-types and same pairs of test blocks. These pairs of difference
scores may be correlated using a Spearman-Brown correction (2 Blocks = 4
correlations, one for each trial=type; 4 Blocks = 8 correlations, one for
each trial type for each pair of test blocks; 6 Blocks = 12 correlations,
one for each trial-type for each pair of test blocks). Each correlation
thus provides a split-half reliability measure for a particular
trial-type for each pair of test blocks.
*The difference scores may be calculated from 300-3000 adjusted latencies
or by calculating separate D measures for odd and even trials in the same
way that single D scores were calculated above for the odd and even trials
This method of calculating split-half reliability was derived from:
De Houwer, J., & De Bruycker, E. (in press). The Implicit Association
Test outperforms the Extrinsic Affective Simon Task as an implicit
measure of interindividual differences in attitudes. British Journal of

Odd and even trials listed in order of presentation separately for each
trial-type and test block. This facilitates calculation of split-half
reliability. First, calculate separate mean latencies for odd and then
even trials for each trial-type within each block (i.e., 2 blocks = 16
means; 4 blocks = 32 means; 6 blocks = 48 means.) Difference scores* can
then be calculated for each pair of consistent and inconsistent blocks
for each trial type for both odd and even trials (i.e., 2 blocks = 8
difference scores; 4 blocks = 16 difference scores; 6 blocks = 24
difference scores). Each participant thus provides pairs of difference
scores (one from odd trials and the other from even trials) for the same
trial-types and same pairs of test blocks. These pairs of difference
scores may be correlated using a Spearman-Brown correction (2 Blocks = 4
correlations, one for each trial=type; 4 Blocks = 8 correlations, one for
each trial type for each pair of test blocks; 6 Blocks = 12 correlations,
one for each trial-type for each pair of test blocks). Each correlation
thus provides a split-half reliability measure for a particular
trial-type for each pair of test blocks.
*The difference scores may be calculated from 300-3000 adjusted latencies
or by calculating separate D measures for odd and even trials in the same
way that single D scores were calculated above for the odd and even trials

Odd and even trials listed in order of presentation separately for each
trial-type and test block. This facilitates calculation of split-half
reliability. First, calculate separate mean latencies for odd and then
even trials for each trial-type within each block (i.e., 2 blocks = 16
means; 4 blocks = 32 means; 6 blocks = 48 means.) Difference scores* can
then be calculated for each pair of consistent and inconsistent blocks
for each trial type for both odd and even trials (i.e., 2 blocks = 8
difference scores; 4 blocks = 16 difference scores; 6 blocks = 24
difference scores). Each participant thus provides pairs of difference
scores (one from odd trials and the other from even trials) for the same
trial-types and same pairs of test blocks. These pairs of difference
scores may be correlated using a Spearman-Brown correction (2 Blocks = 4
correlations, one for each trial=type; 4 Blocks = 8 correlations, one for
each trial type for each pair of test blocks; 6 Blocks = 12 correlations,
one for each trial-type for each pair of test blocks). Each correlation
thus provides a split-half reliability measure for a particular
trial-type for each pair of test blocks.
*The difference scores may be calculated from 300-3000 adjusted latencies
or by calculating separate D measures for odd and even trials in the same
way that single D scores were calculated above for the odd and even trials
This method of calculating split-half reliability was derived from:
De Houwer, J., & De Bruycker, E. (in press). The Implicit Association
Test outperforms the Extrinsic Affective Simon Task as an implicit
measure of interindividual differences in attitudes. British Journal of

Odd and even trials listed in order of presentation separately for each
trial-type and test block. This facilitates calculation of split-half
reliability. First, calculate separate mean latencies for odd and then
even trials for each trial-type within each block (i.e., 2 blocks = 16
means; 4 blocks = 32 means; 6 blocks = 48 means.) Difference scores* can
then be calculated for each pair of consistent and inconsistent blocks
for each trial type for both odd and even trials (i.e., 2 blocks = 8
difference scores; 4 blocks = 16 difference scores; 6 blocks = 24
difference scores). Each participant thus provides pairs of difference
scores (one from odd trials and the other from even trials) for the same
trial-types and same pairs of test blocks. These pairs of difference
scores may be correlated using a Spearman-Brown correction (2 Blocks = 4
correlations, one for each trial=type; 4 Blocks = 8 correlations, one for
each trial type for each pair of test blocks; 6 Blocks = 12 correlations,
one for each trial-type for each pair of test blocks). Each correlation
thus provides a split-half reliability measure for a particular
trial-type for each pair of test blocks.
*The difference scores may be calculated from 300-3000 adjusted latencies
or by calculating separate D measures for odd and even trials in the same
way that single D scores were calculated above for the odd and even trials
This method of calculating split-half reliability was derived from:

measure of interindividual differences in attitudes. British Journal of

Odd and even trials listed in order of presentation separately for each
trial-type and test block. This facilitates calculation of split-half
reliability. First, calculate separate mean latencies for odd and then
even trials for each trial-type within each block (i.e., 2 blocks = 16
means; 4 blocks = 32 means; 6 blocks = 48 means.) Difference scores* can
then be calculated for each pair of consistent and inconsistent blocks
for each trial type for both odd and even trials (i.e., 2 blocks = 8
difference scores; 4 blocks = 16 difference scores; 6 blocks = 24
difference scores). Each participant thus provides pairs of difference
scores (one from odd trials and the other from even trials) for the same
trial-types and same pairs of test blocks. These pairs of difference
scores may be correlated using a Spearman-Brown correction (2 Blocks = 4
correlations, one for each trial=type; 4 Blocks = 8 correlations, one for
each trial type for each pair of test blocks; 6 Blocks = 12 correlations,
one for each trial-type for each pair of test blocks). Each correlation
thus provides a split-half reliability measure for a particular
trial-type for each pair of test blocks.
*The difference scores may be calculated from 300-3000 adjusted latencies
or by calculating separate D measures for odd and even trials in the same
way that single D scores were calculated above for the odd and even trials
This method of calculating split-half reliability was derived from:
De Houwer, J., & De Bruycker, E. (in press). The Implicit Association
Test outperforms the Extrinsic Affective Simon Task as an implicit
measure of interindividual differences in attitudes. British Journal of

Odd and even trials listed in order of presentation separately for each
trial-type and test block. This facilitates calculation of split-half
reliability. First, calculate separate mean latencies for odd and then
even trials for each trial-type within each block (i.e., 2 blocks = 16
means; 4 blocks = 32 means; 6 blocks = 48 means.) Difference scores* can
then be calculated for each pair of consistent and inconsistent blocks
for each trial type for both odd and even trials (i.e., 2 blocks = 8
difference scores; 4 blocks = 16 difference scores; 6 blocks = 24
difference scores). Each participant thus provides pairs of difference
scores (one from odd trials and the other from even trials) for the same
trial-types and same pairs of test blocks. These pairs of difference
scores may be correlated using a Spearman-Brown correction (2 Blocks = 4
correlations, one for each trial=type; 4 Blocks = 8 correlations, one for
each trial type for each pair of test blocks; 6 Blocks = 12 correlations,
one for each trial-type for each pair of test blocks). Each correlation
thus provides a split-half reliability measure for a particular
trial-type for each pair of test blocks.
*The difference scores may be calculated from 300-3000 adjusted latencies
or by calculating separate D measures for odd and even trials in the same
way that single D scores were calculated above for the odd and even trials
This method of calculating split-half reliability was derived from:
De Houwer, J., & De Bruycker, E. (in press). The Implicit Association
Test outperforms the Extrinsic Affective Simon Task as an implicit
measure of interindividual differences in attitudes. British Journal of
